{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e65e3f3c-e458-48df-bf97-1da10fa59aca","content":"To switch to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC), you need to make these changes:\n\n**1. Configure your NuGet.org package** — In NuGet.org, go to your package → Manage → Publishing → add a trusted publisher linking your GitHub repo, branch, and workflow file.\n\n**2. Update your workflow:**\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write  # Required for OIDC token\n      contents: read\n\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n\n      # Build/pack your package...\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n- Add `permissions: id-token: write` to the job\n- **Remove** `--api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}` from the push command\n- No API key or secret needed — the OIDC token is exchanged automatically\n- You can delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` repository secret once confirmed working\n\nThe `dotnet nuget push` CLI (≥ .NET 8 SDK) automatically detects the GitHub OIDC token and uses it to authenticate when no API key is provided and the NuGet source supports trusted publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8c0ce6e6-d174-4a52-b866-5430ad64a39e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key secret to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet publishing - I don't need to search the codebase for this since the working directory isn't a git repository and appears empty.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about what changes are needed to switch to NuGet trusted publishing with OIDC.","outputTokens":445,"requestId":"142B:343824:12AC2E4:14F6683:6A027A57"},"id":"98e6d0a5-da4b-438a-946c-30d4653e8cb7","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:54:57.498Z","parentId":"a2b56324-ff96-42c5-a